Ames House Prices Predictions

Problem Statement: The goal of this project is to develop a predictive model that can accurately estimate the sale prices of residential properties in the city of Ames, Iowa, using the Ames Housing Dataset from Kaggle. The prediction model will be based on a comprehensive set of features describing various aspects of the properties, such as their size, location, condition, and features. This predictive model will be valuable for real estate agents, property investors, and potential buyers to make informed decisions regarding property transactions.

Background: The city of Ames, located in the state of Iowa, has a diverse real estate market with properties of various types, sizes, and characteristics. Accurately estimating the value of a property is a crucial task for both buyers and sellers. Machine learning techniques provide an opportunity to create predictive models that can capture complex relationships between property attributes and sale prices.

Dataset: The dataset for this project consists of historical data on residential property sales in Ames. Each data point represents a property sale and includes various features describing the property, such as its lot size, neighborhood, construction date, number of bedrooms, and more. The target variable is the sale price of the property. The dataset includes both categorical and numerical features, as well as missing values that need to be handled appropriately.

Objective: The main objective of this project is to build a robust predictive model that can accurately predict the sale price of residential properties based on their features. The model should be trained on historical data and then evaluated on a separate test dataset to ensure its generalization ability. Performance metrics such as Mean Squared Error (MSE) and Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) will be used to assess the model's predictive accuracy.

# Plot histograms for columns that we want

# Input:
# dataframe: a DataFrame
# list_of_columns : columns of the dataframe that we want to plot - list of string
# list_of_titles : titles of columns that we want to plot - list of string

def subplot_histograms(dataframe, list_of_columns, list_of_titles, figsize = (20,5), ncol = 4):
    nrows = int(np.ceil(len(list_of_columns)/ncol)) # Makes sure you have enough rows
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows, ncols=ncol,figsize = figsize)
    ax = ax.ravel() # Ravel turns a matrix into a vector, which is easier to iterate
    for i, column in enumerate(list_of_columns): # Gives us an index value to get into all our lists
        ax[i].hist(dataframe[column]) 
        ax[i].set_title(list_of_titles[i])

In [23]:
# Normally people will use 1.5, but I will use 3 to be more conservative
min_val = q25 - 3*iqr
max_val = q75 + 3*iqr
In [24]:
outlier_row = [X[(X[col] < min_val[i]) | (X[col] > max_val[i])].index for i, col in enumerate(remaining_numerical_col)]

# Plot scatters plot for columns that we want

# Input:
# dataframe: a DataFrame
# list_of_columns : columns of the dataframe that we want to plot - list of string
# list_of_titles : titles of columns that we want to plot - list of string

def subplot_scatter(dataframe, list_of_columns, list_of_titles, figsize = (20,5), ncol = 3):
    nrows = int(np.ceil(len(list_of_columns)/ncol)) # Makes sure you have enough rows
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows, ncols=ncol,figsize = figsize)
    ax = ax.ravel() # Ravel turns a matrix into a vector, which is easier to iterate
    for i, column in enumerate(list_of_columns): # Gives us an index value to get into all our lists
        ax[i].scatter(dataframe[column],y) 
        ax[i].set_title(list_of_titles[i])

plt.figure()
for i in range(0,15,3):
    subplot_scatter(X,remaining_numerical_col[i:i+3],remaining_numerical_col[i:i+3])

Handle Multicollinearity

  • We are going to check which features are highly correlated with each other using the threshold of 0.8. If the correlation between those features is greater than 0.8, we will remove either one of them
In [31]:
X = X[remaining_numerical_col + category_columns]
In [32]:
correlation = X.corr()
In [33]:
set([" and ".join(sorted([col, ind])) 
     for col in correlation.columns 
     for ind in correlation.index 
     if abs(correlation.loc[ind,col]) > 0.8 and col != ind])
Out[33]:
{'1st_Flr_SF and Total_Bsmt_SF',
 'Garage_Area and Garage_Cars',
 'Garage_Yr_Blt and Year_Built',
 'Gr_Liv_Area and TotRms_AbvGrd'}

  • After checking, we can see that the following features are highly correlated:

    • 1st Flr SF and Total Bsmt SF
    • Garage Area and Garage Cars
    • Garage Yr Blt and Year Built
    • Gr Liv Area and TotRms AbvGrd

  • Total_Bsmt_SF, Garage_Cars, Year_Built and TotRms_AbvGrd columns will be removed

In [34]:
X.drop(columns= ["Total_Bsmt_SF", "Garage_Cars", "Year_Built", "TotRms_AbvGrd"], inplace = True)

Data Imputation

In [35]:
# Updated numerical and category columns
remaining_numerical_col = [i for i in remaining_numerical_col if i not in ["Total_Bsmt_SF", "Garage_Cars", "Year_Built", "TotRms_AbvGrd"] ]
category_columns = [i for i in category_columns if i not in ["Total_Bsmt_SF", "Garage_Cars", "Year_Built", "TotRms_AbvGrd"] ]
In [36]:
# Perform mean imputation, and standard scaler for numerical columns
clean_numerical = [([i],[SimpleImputer(), StandardScaler()]) for i in remaining_numerical_col]
In [37]:
# Perform most frequent imputation, and LabelBinarizer for category columns
clean_categorical = [([i],[SimpleImputer(strategy = "most_frequent"), MultiLabelBinarizer()]) for i in category_columns]
